At the top is one of these ESP32 camera boards with a camera featuring a fisheye lens and an IR LED, which I took from a Raspberry Pi camera.
The reason for the strange shape of this plastic box is the swiveling side wall of the nesting box. I bought it like that and couldn't change it, so I had to build around it.
Since there's no power in the garden, the whole thing is powered by a solar panel and a 2600 mAh 18650 cell.
I didn't photograph the cell or the charger, but here's a picture of the panel.
In the grey box hanging next to the nesting box is the battery.
If it's fully charged, I have an uptime of about 4 hours.
I'll call that a feature. So, the birds also get some private space.
At first, I wasn't sure if the internet in our garden would be enough for this setup. The old access points that I replaced last year in autumn wouldn't have been enough.
But the new ones cover this area very well.
That's almost a shame, because I had planned to install a TP-Link cpe210 on the roof and arrange it downwards into the garden.
Perhaps I'll do that again when/if I set up more nesting boxes with cameras. I probably need it in areas further away from the house.
The camera is offline now and I don't know why. It just turned off an hour after sunset.
Maybe the battery didn't charge any further three hours before sunset because there wasn't enough light.
Or something less than half a day was not enough to fully charge the battery.
I'll probably have to wait and see what happens tomorrow.
I have no battery telemetry. I will probably have to change that in the future.
Generally, a few more sensors would be a good thing, I think.
And maybe a battery that is at least theoretically able to keep the thing running overnight.
Ah yes, and another lens.
